narratives.question_text: How would you summarize ECON 110 05 for a fellow student? Would you recommend ECON 110 05 to another student? Why or why not?
comments: I would recommend this class to students only if they are willing to be self-disciplined with complicated readings and materials. We were never tested on readings in the traditional way, but had I not read I would not have benefited from the class nearly as much as I did. You will learn a lot, but also work a lot (and think a LOT). Also only take the class if you are comfortable with a loose structure of learning and curriculum scheduling.

Good course, a lot of interesting material and you come away with a great perspective on what makes a democracy work--and what makes it fail. Professor Stanley asks the hard questions and is very interested in the answers--and you will be too. There's a lot of reading but not too many assignments. Could be more class discussion.
I would recommend Philosophy 083 to a fellow student because it is a very engaging and rewarding course. You learn so much.
It was a small seminar class that introduces the student to several well-known political philosophy texts. Take this course if you have an interest in learning about democracy or democratic theory.

A great class that allows individuals to become philosophers themselves with the assistance of the great works of other philosophers. Great class to learn how to question and think critically as a writer and reader.
